  "key_findings": {
    "synthetic_vs_real": "Synthetic data produced higher MCC (0.714 vs 0.622) due to engineered feature-target relationships. Real Kaggle data had only 2-3 features with strong predictive signal (Suicidal Thoughts r=0.55, Academic Pressure r=0.47).",
    "loss_function": "Switching from MSE to Binary Cross-Entropy improved AUC-ROC from 0.942 to 0.952 and recall from 79% to 93%, at the cost of precision.",
    "layer_depth": "Increasing from 5 to 6 layers improved performance. However, 8 layers showed no improvement over 6, suggesting barren plateau effects in the variational landscape.",
    "learning_rate": "Learning rate decay (0.01 → 0.005 at midpoint) consistently improved convergence. Fine-tuning with lower LR pushed loss from 0.44 to 0.38.",
    "threshold_optimization": "Lowering threshold from 0.5 to 0.45 boosted recall by ~14% at the cost of ~8% precision. For mental health screening, this recall-prioritized approach reduces false negatives — the more dangerous error type.",
    "clinical_significance": "The selected model's MCC of 0.714 significantly outperforms the estimated 0.5 human baseline for informal mental health screening. The 86.5% recall means the system identifies 87 out of 100 at-risk students."
  }
